'''Anthony of Tagrit'''<ref>''Antun of Tragrit'' by John W. Watt, in Sebastian Brock et al. (eds.), ''Gorgias Encyclopedic Dictionary of Syriac Heritage'', Piscataway, Gorgias Press, 2011, p. 23.</ref> ({{lang-syc|ܐܢܛܘܢܝܘܣ ܕܬܓܪܝܬ}}, also known as '''Antonius Rhetor''') was a 9th-century [[Syriac Orthodox Church|West Syrian]] [[Assyrian people|Syriac]] theologian and rhetor. Anthony was based in [[Tagrit]] and is best remembered for his contribution to [[Syriac literature]].<ref name="Schadé2006">{{cite book|last=Schadé|first=Johannes P.|title=Encyclopedia of World Religions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XRkfKdho-5cC&pg=PT63|accessdate=23 June 2013|year=2006|publisher=Foreign Media Group|isbn=978-1-60136-000-7|page=63}}</ref> One of his few surviving works ''The Book of the Rhetoric'' ({{lang|syc|ܥܠ ܝܕܥܬܐ ܕܪܗܝܛܪܘܬܐ}}) was translated to several languages including English.<ref>''The Fifth Book of the Rhetoric of Antony of Tagrit'', Louvain, Peeters, 1986.</ref>

