[[File:Antti Tuuri2.jpg|thumb|250px|Antti Tuuri (2009)]] '''Antti Elias Tuuri''' (born 1 October 1944, [[Kauhava]], [[Southern Ostrobothnia]]) is a [[Finnish people|Finnish]] writer, known for his works dealing with [[Southern Ostrobothnia]].
The ''Äitini-suku''-series tells the stories of the Finns who emigrated to the United States. He received the [[J. H. Erkko Award]] in 1971 for ''Asioiden suhteet ja Lauantaina illalla'', [[The Nordic Council's Literature Prize]] in 1985 for ''Pohjanmaa'', and the [[Finlandia Prize]] in 1997 for his novel ''Lakeuden kutsu''. Tuuri has also translated some Icelandic [[saga]]s.
Many of his novels have been made into films including ''[[Rukajärven tie]]'' also known as "Ambush" in English, about the [[Continuation War]] 1941-44 in Karelia, Russia and ''[[Talvisota (film)|Talvisota]]'', the Winter War 1939-1940.
