{{short description|News story in a gossip column where subjects are anonymous}}
{{refimprove|date=August 2012}}
A '''blind item''' is a [[news story]], typically in a [[Gossip columnist|gossip column]], in which the details of the matter are reported while the identities of the people involved are not revealed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2016/10/crazy-days-and-nights-enty-interview|title=The King of the Hollywood Blind Item Reveals All|last=Bonner|first=Mehera|work=Vanities|access-date=2018-04-28|language=en}}</ref> The invention of the blind item is credited to [[William d'Alton Mann]] (1839&ndash;1920), publisher of ''[[Town Topics (magazine)|Town Topics]]'', who often used it for [[blackmail]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Gossiper Silenced |date= Jan 25, 1932 |work=[[Time Magazine]] |url= http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,743014,00.html |accessdate= Aug 8, 2008 |subscription= yes }}</ref> [[Communication privacy management theory]] relates to the ideas of [[information privacy]] that influence this form of communication.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McNealy|first=Jasmine|last2=Mullis|first2=Michaela Devyn|date=March 2019|title=Tea and turbulence: Communication privacy management theory and online celebrity gossip forums|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0747563218305193|journal=Computers in Human Behavior|volume=92|pages=110–118|doi=10.1016/j.chb.2018.10.029|issn=0747-5632|via=}}</ref> The advent of gossip websites brought about more public debate and speculation about the individual blind item stories, and also about the ethics surrounding the practice.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ortner|first=Heike|date=2013|title=Not So Blind Items: Anonymous Celebrity Gossip Exposed|url=http://web.mit.edu/comm-forum/legacy/mit8/papers/Ortner_MIT8_Blind_Items.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Audiences might use blind item material as a shared topic of conversation with peers, and perhaps even as a conversational entry point to a sensitive topic that is personal to them.<ref>{{Cite thesis|last=Petersen|first=Anne Helen|title=The gossip industry : producing and distributing star images, celebrity gossip and entertainment news 1910-2010|date=May 2011|degree=|publisher=The University of Texas at Austin|url=https://repositories.lib.utexas.edu/handle/2152/11454|doi=}}</ref>

