{{Infobox language |name=Nomatsiguenga |nativename=inato |states=[[Perú]] |ethnicity=[[Machiguenga people|Machiguenga]] |speakers=6,500 |date=2003 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Maipurean languages|Arawakan]] |fam2=Southern |fam3=[[Campa languages|Campa]] |fam4=Matsigenka |iso3=not |glotto=noma1263 |glottorefname=Nomatsiguenga }}
'''Nomatsiguenga''' (Matsigenka) is an [[Arawakan language]] of [[Peru]]. It is close enough to [[Machiguenga language|Machiguenga]] to sometimes be considered dialects of a single language, especially given that both are spoken by the [[Machiguenga people]]. Most speakers are monolingual.
==Grammar== Nomatsiguenga is one of the few languages in the world that has two different [[causative]] mechanisms to denote whether the causer was involved in the activity with the causee or not. The prefix ''ogi-'' is used to express the idea that the causer was ''not'' involved in the activity, while the suffix ''-hag'' is used when the causer ''is'' involved.<ref>Wise, M.R. (1986). "Grammatical characteristics of PreAndine Arawaken languages of Peru." pg. 567–642. In Derbyshire, D. C. & Pullum, G. K., eds. (1986). ''Handbook of Amazonian languages, Vol. 1'''. Berlin: Mouton de Gruyter. Cited in Dixon, R.M.W. (2000). "A Typology of Causatives: Form, Syntax, and Meaning". In Dixon, R.M.W. & Aikhenvald, Alexendra Y. Changing Valency: Case Studies in Transitivity. Cambridge University Press.</ref>
:{| |- | y-'''ogi'''-monti-ë-ri || i-tomi |- | 3sg+{{sc|m}}-'''{{sc|caus}}<sub>1</sub>'''-cross.river-{{sc|non.fut}}-3sg+{{sc|m}} || 3sg+{{sc|m}}-son |- | colspan=2| "He made his son cross the river (he told him to)." |}
:{| |- | y-monti-a-'''hag'''-ë-ri || i-tomi |- | 3sg+{{sc|m}}-cross.river-{{sc|epenthetic}}-'''{{sc|caus}}<sub>2</sub>'''-{{sc|non.fut}}-3sg+{{sc|m}} || 3sg+{{sc|m}}-son |- | colspan=2| "He made his son cross the river (he helped him across)." |}
